helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Tracy Buczek, Earlier today around 10:30 am the fax servers crashed which prevented the sending of faxes through our network. At around 2:30 the server was back up, so hopefully your problem should be resolved. In your case we saw that two faxes had been sent out when the servers went back up. If this is not the case please contact us with the further issues.
Respectfully, Collin DeOcampo TIER 1 SUPPORT TEAM 414.277.7288 Submit a Service Request: helpdesk@msoe.edu Twitter: @MSOE-IT
"We are building a culture of exceptional customer service!"

helpdesk-ticket.description:

Angela called back saying she can go ahead and remove the fee or even reduce it if needed, but she needs confirmation from a full-time IT department employee (probably Ben).
The student's name is: Ali Aleef

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Marc Dannecker, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/17407
There are two issues that are the most common cause of this problem, which are having multiple versions of Java installed, and not having the ADP site on the list of trusted websites. Java has an issue with having multiple versions installed, where the two versions will fight over which one gets control of a program and never actually get any work done. To see if you have multiple versions of Java installed, open the start menu and type "Programs and Features", and open that. The programs are listed in alphabetically order, so you can just scroll down to the J's to see if there are multiple Java versions. If there are, uninstall all of them and then install the newest version, either from Software Center or from java.com. Even if you have only the most recent version of Java installed, Internet Explorer still may refuse to use it, because it will only use plug-ins on websites that you have explicitly told it are trusted. To add a website to the trusted list, click on the little gear-shaped icon in the top right of the window and click on Internet Options. A new window will open, and from there click on the Security tab, click on the green check mark that says Trusted Sites, and click on the Sites button. A new window will open that allows you to modify the trusted list; it automatically has the current site entered in the box, so if you were on the ADP site already all you have to do is click on the Add button. If you still have issues with ADP after this, we can send a technician over to look at the issue.
Respectfully,
Samuel Conroy
TIER 2 SUPPORT TEAM
(414) 277-2833 Submit a Service Request: helpdesk@msoe.edu

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Multi-Purpose Room - Audio Issues
helpdesk-ticket.description:
The video works fine when using VGA cable from laptop to port on wall. But, there are audio issues:
Tried different aux cables, different VGA+aux cables, and a phone on the aux cord. All produce an extremely faint sound when connected to the 1/8" audio in, on the wall port - right above the VGA input. Messed with the volume meter control on the panel as well. Tried turning the system off and on using the wall panel buttons.
The wireless microphone works completely fine with a very loud sound - while the aux audio in only produces that faint sound.
Ended up just placing the microphone on a laptop speaker and that actually sounded surprisingly fine.
- Kyle Brown

I have rebooted the laptop, reset the wireless connection, connected via ethernet, verified DNS settings
helpdesk-ticket.description-html:
• I am unable to access our SSO page from my Mac laptop (OS 10.12). 
  • I can reach the page from my work laptop (EliteBook 8560w/Windows 7). 
  • I can reach other public facing web pages for MSOE (Blackboard, my.msoe)
  • I can reach Microsoft's Office365 page, but when I try to log in with my credentials, it cannot access the AD server to verify.

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Sean Jones,
When you aren't able to access the page, what is shown by your browser? Besides that, it's possible that your mac keychain is attempting to auto sign you on with your old password and therefore will not load the page, so updating the password on your mac keychain may solve the problem. Below is an article outlining how to do so.
https://support.apple.com/kb/PH25230?locale=en_US Please let us know! Thank you!
Respectfully, Sabrina Stangler TIER 1 SUPPORT TEAM 414.277.7288 Submit a Service Request: helpdesk@msoe.edu Twitter: @MSOE-IT

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Sean Jones, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/17456
In regard to accessing, adfs.msoe.edu/adfs/ls/, the page you are seeing with the message, "an error occurred" is completely normal. Users should not be able to access this page directly due to the way it is set up. I have verified the same error message when attempting to access the page on my computer as well. One can see from going to https://outlook.com/owa/msoe.edu and being redirected to SSO, that the page requires a "client request id" along with loads of other information. When accessing adfs.msoe.edu/adfs/ls alone, the program does not have enough information to do its job, resulting in the error message that we both experienced.
We are performing server maintenance this weekend, but SSO is currently up and running.
Respectfully, Gerry TIER 1 SUPPORT TEAM 414.277.7288 Submit a Service Request: helpdesk@msoe.edu Twitter: @MSOE-IT
"We are building a culture of exceptional customer service!"

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Sahasraramans, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/17476
I looked into this for you and there is an issue on our end that is affecting Global Protect that we are working to resolve. Others are also having this issue, so I would like to thank you for bringing this to our attention. We sent out a campus-wide notice via email on May 12th with the following text:
Dear Faculty, Staff and Students, This email is an update to an earlier notice we sent regarding emergency maintenance this weekend. Due to the severity of the issue, we will be updating servers starting immediately and continue throughout the weekend. During this time there may be temporary disruptions to network services. We will also be deploying an update to all computers. You will be prompted to restart your computer after it has been installed which we encourage you to do as soon as possible. We believe that there is minimal risk with this update however if you experience issues accessing shared files on network drives please content the helpdesk. We apologize for any inconvenience this may cause and thank you for your patience and cooperation.
Respectfully, Michael LeRoy TIER 1 SUPPORT TEAM 414.277.7288 Submit a Service Request: helpdesk@msoe.edu Twitter: @MSOE-IT
"We are building a culture of exceptional customer service!"

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Poster printing
helpdesk-ticket.description: User was having difficulty printing his poster with the background on it in the senior design lab, asked us to print it.
helpdesk-ticket.description-html: User was having difficulty printing his poster with the background on it in the senior design lab, asked us to print it.

helpdesk-note.body:
The poster was created in Publisher and couldn't be saved to a pdf (would not save the entire poster, just a chunk from the middle). The page dimensions in the project were 22x32, so copying and pasting wasn't an option. Eventually got the poster to print 45 minutes later after saving it as a png, inserting that into a powerpoint, saving that as a pdf, and a couple of prints because the dimensions given by the customer were not accurate to the size of the board they were trying to put it on, so I did some estimations and calculations and got it close enough that the customer could use it with minor alterations.
-Brenna

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Jacob Frey, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/17484
We can exchange your laptop if that's what it comes down to, but I'd like to see if there's anything we can do to work around the issue until you can come back to the States. How long will it be until then? If it's not too far away, you can follow the instructions linked below to reinstall Office.

Please let us know if this solution will work for you, and if not, how you would like to proceed.

In the software center, the was an update showing, so I installed the update. I then restarted. During the restart, I received a message stating that the update failed and Windows was undoing the changes. It restarted fine after that. The software center still shows an update pending:
[cid:image001.png@01D2D0F0.85079200]
Although it seems to say that it is now installed based on the image above - said requires restart just before, seeming to indicate that it was still pending.
Global Protect VPN is still giving with the “Password expires in 0 days” message.
So, in summary, all is working ok, even with messages, and I am not sure if that update is really installed or not.
Mitch Colton

So, in summary, all is working ok, even with messages, and I am not sure if that update is really installed or not.
 
Mitch Colton

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Re: Box
helpdesk-ticket.description:
Hello, Can you help me with Box.com? Dave Schmitz sent me a folder on box. It does not appear in my box list of folders, I can only see the information when I click on view file through my email. What do I need to do?
Thanks, Dawn Dawn Blessing Administrative Assistant Rader School of Business (414) 277-7279 www.msoe.edu
helpdesk-ticket.description-html:
Hello,
Can you help me with Box.com?  Dave Schmitz sent me a folder on box.  It does not appear in my box list of folders, I can only see the information when I click on view file through my email.  What do I need to do?
 
Thanks, Dawn
Dawn Blessing
Administrative Assistant
Rader School of Business
(414) 277-7279
www.msoe.edu

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Dawn Blessing, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/17517
There are two different ways to share a folder in Box. The first one is to share a link, which will allow anyone with that link to view that folder, even if they're not on Box. If this is how the folder was shared with you, it will not show up in your folders.
The second method is inviting collaborators. This will allow a folder to show up in multiple users' box accounts.
It looks like the folder was shared with you using the first method, so to access the folder you will need to use the link that Dave Schmitz emailed to you.
Please let me know if you have any more questions.
Respectfully, Paul Page TIER 1 SUPPORT TEAM 414.277.7288 Submit a Service Request: helpdesk@msoe.edu Twitter: @MSOE-IT
"We are building a culture of exceptional customer service!"

The second method is inviting collaborators. This will allow a folder to show up in multiple users' box accounts. 

It looks like the folder was shared with you using the first method, so to access the folder you will need to use the link that Dave Schmitz emailed to you.

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Chas Boyer, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/17641
It looks like your friend had a different problem than you, he was not able to log into the VPN but you are not able to log into your computer itself. There is a different process for fixing both. What kind of error is it giving you when you are trying to log in? Expired password or something about a trust relationship issue? For the trust relationship issue all you have to do to log in is turn off your wifi, we would be able to permanently fix it if we had the machine, but this is a work around for now so you can use your laptop.
As per not hearing back about your previous problems, it seems as though we did reply to your issue about being taken off of the domain as well as needing admin priveledges yesterday and two days ago to your msoe email boyerct@msoe.edu. In a nutshell there is nothing that we can do from here about that since we would need the computer to physically be here to run our scripts on it.
Seeing your domain issue, that would explain why you are not able to log into your computer, but disabling the wifi should the issue.
Respectfully, Karolina Klimont TIER 1 SUPPORT TEAM 414.277.7288 Submit a Service Request: helpdesk@msoe.edu Twitter: @MSOE-IT

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Dr.Meier is unable to use his computer after he got updates from IT.
helpdesk-ticket.description: He is unable to any work with his computer unless he is plugged into an external monitor. He said this issue occurred once updates were pushed through from IT. He is also unable to see what the updates where pushed through in software center.
helpdesk-ticket.description-html: He is unable to any work with his computer unless he is plugged into an external monitor. He said this issue occurred once updates were pushed through from IT. He is also unable to see what the updates where pushed through in software center.

helpdesk-note.body:
Just to inform anyone reading this ticket. This is a weird graphical issue that happened months ago and has apparently happened to multiple faculty members with tablets. Only has issues on the touchscreen monitor. External monitors look completely fine. Peter has worked with Dr. Meier on this. Not sure if a reimage has been attempted.
Side note: There needs to me more information in tickets as well as reasoning for why tickets get pushed to different groups. Sending back to tier 1 as this is faculty and there is no information on a request for us to go meet with him.
helpdesk-note.body-html:
Just to inform anyone reading this ticket. This is a weird graphical issue that happened months ago and has apparently happened to multiple faculty members with tablets. Only has issues on the touchscreen monitor. External monitors look completely fine. Peter has worked with Dr. Meier on this. Not sure if a reimage has been attempted.

Side note:
There needs to me more information in tickets as well as reasoning for why tickets get pushed to different groups. Sending back to tier 1 as this is faculty and there is no information on a request for us to go meet with him.

helpdesk-note.body: I can now use the laptop display again. I told Windows through Windows-P to "use second screen only." This caused the driver to power-off/blank the LCD panel but apparently differently than a screen close or a power-off cycle as those techniques did not work. Then, an "unplug" of the external monitor caused Windows to unblank the LCD panel and all was resolved. Please talk to Peter Pfister. This was an elevation of a known issue for multiple laptops (Derek Riley, Darrin Rothe, me, and others) that have exhibited sporadic "rastering" behavior. This is not a hardware issue as the bios startup screen does not raster, nor does the bios setup screen. This is a Windows issue or an MSOE image issue. HP Support Assistant and Windows Update both report that the display device driver is up-to-date and that no updates are available for it. Whatever you pushed yesterday/today made the issue much worse. Prior, a simple two-times reboot would usually result in stability. Today, event 10 reboots left the screen rastering. Luckily, I found the technique described above and hope that it works in the future if needed. I will also note that whatever you pushed does not show up in Software Center under installed items. They should. Even if MSOE is managing the computers, I would hope that users know exactly what MSOE has done to them.
helpdesk-note.body-html:
I can now use the laptop display again. I told Windows through Windows-P to "use second screen only." This caused the driver to power-off/blank the LCD panel but apparently differently than a screen close or a power-off cycle as those techniques did not work. Then, an "unplug" of the external monitor caused Windows to unblank the LCD panel and all was resolved. Please talk to Peter Pfister. This was an elevation of a known issue for multiple laptops (Derek Riley, Darrin Rothe, me, and others) that have exhibited sporadic "rastering" behavior. This is not a hardware issue as the bios startup screen does not raster, nor does the bios setup screen. This is a Windows issue or an MSOE image issue. HP Support Assistant and Windows Update both report that the display device driver is up-to-date and that no updates are available for it. 

Whatever you pushed yesterday/today made the issue much worse. Prior, a simple two-times reboot would usually result in stability. Today, event 10 reboots left the screen rastering. Luckily, I found the technique described above and hope that it works in the future if needed. 

I will also note that whatever you pushed does not show up in Software Center under installed items. They should. Even if MSOE is managing the computers, I would hope that users know exactly what MSOE has done to them.

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Kristine Wesson, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/17597
I'm sorry that the domain migration caused you to have issues with your H drive, in order for you to be able to access it again you just have to remap it, I will include the instructions below:
1. Click the “Start” button on your device. 2. On Windows 7, go to “Computer” and on Windows 10 go to “File Explorer” and then “This PC”. 3. Click “Map network drive” at the top of the screen. 4. Select the drive you wish to add (H:) in the “Drive” dropdown menu. 5. In the “Folder” box type the folder you wish to add a) For H type: \\homestore\homedrives$\your username 6. Check the “Reconnect at logon box” 7. If you are using an MSOE issued device with trusted domain credentials, do not check the “Connect using different credentials” box. If you are on a personal device, you will need to check this box. These credentials will be your domain trusted MSOE username and password. 8. Click “Finish” 9. If you have permissions to access the drive, you will now be able to use it.
I hope this helps! please let us know if you have any questions.
Respectfully, Karolina Klimont TIER 1 SUPPORT TEAM 414.277.7288 Submit a Service Request: helpdesk@msoe.edu Twitter: @MSOE-IT
"We are building a culture of exceptional customer service!"

Today we discovered that the auto-power off was set to 30-minutes on one of the projectors. Thanks,
Zach Boyd

helpdesk-ticket.subject: User was concerned about a potential virus on his laptop
helpdesk-ticket.description: The antivirus kaspersky suddenly appeared (due to our updates) on the computers managed by the user. He was concerned it could be a virus as it told him windows defender was turned off. He called for confirmarion,
helpdesk-ticket.description-html: The antivirus kaspersky suddenly appeared (due to our updates) on the computers managed by the user. He was concerned it could be a virus as it told him windows defender was turned off. He called for confirmarion,

helpdesk-note.body:
Convinced him that kaspersky was in a fact an anti-virus. He was concerned about ransomware and I told him this program was installed to prevent such attacks. He did raise a good point about informing users of the antivirus installation. I check through the emails I got about the updates and none mentioned kaspersky, so it makes sense that it would cause concern.
-Brenna
